erpretive methods, literary knowledge challenges our dominant narrative of the scientific revolution as the sine qua non of epistemological innovation in the British Enlightenment. With its recourse to imagination as a more reliable source of truth than any empirical account, literary knowledge facilitates a redefinition of authority and evidence, as well as of the self and society, implicitly articulating the difference that would come to distinguish the arts and sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismx18th century. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnlightenmentxGreat Britain. 0aEnlightenmentzGreat Britain. 0aImagination. 0aKnowledge, Theory ofxHistoryx18th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aKnowledge, Theory ofzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aLiterature and sciencexHistoryx18th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aLiterature and sciencezGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 4aBritish Enlightenment. 4aaesthetics. 4adrama. 4aepistemology. 4aexperiment. 4aimagination. 4aliterature. 4apoetry. 4aprose. 4ascience. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503606456zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606456.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles